By the turn of the century leadership in the black community was predictably reflective of these occupational, residential, and social constraints. In a 1903 Christmas supplement of the Journal-News, a Republican daily, the editor, William W. Ross, featured the civic leaders of the city in such categories as law, religion, medicine, and government. Listed at the end of the publication—and in no business or professional categories—were only two black leaders, S. S. Dupee and J. D. Rouse. Dupee, a physician, was described as "the most prominent and well-to-do-colored man in Evansville ." He was head of
