the Indiana Knights and Daughters of Tabor, founder of two drug stores, editor of the "Colored Column" of the Journal-News, and Republican politician who had demonstrated his influence by thwarting the "few colored Democrats" who had tried "to decoy his people to ruin." Rouse, pastor of Liberty Baptist Church, was pictured as a noted orator who had built his church to a membership of 2,000 and become an officer of the National Baptist Convention. He was praised as a model father as well, since both of his children were local school teachers.42
